summary: A trainer I had had me using machines instead of free weights to "develop a good foundation". Should I give this any credence?...
title: A trainer I had had me using machines instead of free weights to "develop a good foundation". Should I give this any credence? via /r/Fitness
body:
I don’t have the money to afford to go to a good gym right now so I’m stuck with Planet Fitness. I read through the FAQ and I know it addresses machines to some degree, but I’d like some more information if that’s okay. The FAQ says it will cause problems with actually using muscles in day to day life, but I want to know if using machines primarily will actually majorly impact muscle growth?

I had a personal trainer a few years ago and he kept me on machines for quite some time to, as he put it, develop a good foundation. When he had me start using free weights I think I found them easier to use than I’m currently finding them, but I can’t really remember it well. Is using machines for a couple months, after which I’ll be able to afford a Gold’s Gym membership, to develop a good foundation a good rationale or was my trainer misguided? I know there’s a lot of exercises I can do with dumbbells, but I’m really struggling to use them, for dumbbell bench presses in particular, and based on what my trainer told me I’m somewhat convinced that machines can be a good way to start. Thanks for your time!



Submitted August 29, 2018 at 11:24PM by Warmtongue
via reddit https://ift.tt/2omQsBX

title: Deadlifts and lower back “pain” via /r/Fitness
body:
Hey all! Had a quick question in regards to deadlifts and muscle tightness/back pain. I typically don’t do deadlifts, but I started a new program - ICF 5X5. It says to do 1 X 5, but I did 3 X 5 instead. Looking back, I plan to follow the plan to the dot, but just wanted to do more. I’ve done deadlifts before, but not in a really long time and believe my form was pretty good, flat back, knees slightly bent, lifting with legs, but I’m noticing lower back tightness/soreness/pain? Is it normal to feel this tightness when coming back to an exercise you haven’t done in a long time?



Submitted August 30, 2018 at 05:07AM by DinoChaur
via reddit https://ift.tt/2wqjJ2Y
